      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Indeed, you've got it right. If you're paying $300 a month and $125 of that is interest, then $175 is going towards reducing the principal. As the principal balance decreases, the interest portion of your payment should also decrease, assuming the interest rate remains constant.\n\nHowever, there are a few things that could cause the interest to stay higher than you expect:\n\n1. **Fees and Penalties**: Some loans have fees or penalties for late payments, late payments, or even for making payments less than the minimum required. These can add to the total amount you owe, increasing the interest.\n\n2. **Variable Interest Rates**: If your loan has a variable interest rate, it could change over time. If the rate increases, your interest charges will go up as well.\n\n3. **Amortization Schedule**: The way your loan is amortized can affect how much interest you pay over time. Some loans are structured so that more interest is paid in the early years, with less principal paid off initially.\n\n4. **Interest Capitalization**: If you have a deferred payment plan or if you're in forbearance, any unpaid interest may be added to the principal balance, increasing the amount of interest you owe.\n\n5.",
